After we trained our model, we need a easy way to recognize images, so we have the following funciton that recizes and feeds an imput image to our model.¶

The function predOut function takes an image of size (64x64) i.e. a window, then finds its HOG features, and finally scale it using the same scaler we used prevously.¶

It reutrns 1 if there is a car and 0 otherwize.¶

In [140]:
def predOut(img2):
    from skimage.feature import hog
    img = img2.copy() # assumed 64x64
    img_hog = hog(img, orientations=9, pixels_per_cell=(8, 8),cells_per_block=(2, 2), visualize=False, multichannel=False)

    sc = scaler.transform(img_hog.reshape(1,-1))
    pred = model.predict(sc)
    
    return int(pred)

Testing predOut(), we clearly see that the image contains multiple cars. So, if we scale it to 64x64 it will have many cars in that small space, wich will be seen as noise and thereby a street by the model.¶

To fix this we implemented the sliding window technique¶

To solve that issue we need some sort of a sliding window that runs over the image, predicting every portion of it without minimal data loss due to recizing. That way we can take the cars by themselves for example.¶

The following funciton reco() implements the sliding window method. It recognizes portions of the image by inputting that porion into the model.¶

Parameters

  • slide_ratio: percentage of overlap in sliding window
  • img: the image to be recognized
  • win_sz: the size of the sliding window. The defualt is 64x64
  • rand_selection: if set to `true` it will reduce the number of squares in the output image

Returns:

  • ios: this is the `indecies of squares` (cooredinates of top left corner) of the recognition as a list
  • image(called image2): the original image with the reconition boxes drawn over it
In [142]:
def reco(img,div_size=None,win_sz=None,rand_selection=True,slide_ratio=1/4):
    ios = []
    img2 = img.copy()
    if (div_size!=None):
        new_x_dim = int(img2.shape[1]/div_size)
        new_y_dim = int(img2.shape[0]/div_size)
        img2 = cv2.resize(img2,(new_x_dim,new_y_dim))
        img2 = cv2.GaussianBlur(img2,(1,1),cv2.BORDER_DEFAULT) # don't know how much is needed
    
    copy1 = img2.copy()
    copy2 = img2.copy()
    
    if(win_sz==None):
        window_size = 64 # 64 X 64 this is the default window size
    else:
        window_size = win_sz
    
    window = np.ones((window_size,window_size))

    i=0
    while (i + window_size) < (copy1.shape[0]) : # y , vertical
        j=0
        while (j + window_size) < (copy1.shape[1]): # x , horizontal
            
            window = copy1[i:window_size+i,j:window_size+j] # copy[vertical, horizontal]

            if predOut(window): # window
                if(np.random.randint(0,3)==0 and rand_selection): # 33.33% chance of drawing box = less boxes
                    copy2 = cv2.rectangle(copy2, (j,i), (j+window_size,i+window_size ), (255,0,0), 2)
                    ios.append((j,i))
                elif(not rand_selection):
                    copy2 = cv2.rectangle(copy2, (j,i), (j+window_size,i+window_size ), (255,0,0), 2)
                    ios.append((j,i))

            j+= int(window_size*slide_ratio)
        i+= int(window_size*slide_ratio)

    return copy2,ios #indecies of squares

Eventhough we ware able to recognize the cars, we actually are predicting the cars more than once. That, can affect how we deal with collision avoidance in the future.¶

One way to solve this issue is to see were the areas that have the greates recogntion rate are, and just draw one box represing that hot area. That tichniqe is called heatmaps¶

The following function heat_map_over() calculates the heat of the recognition. It then finds the most overlap in that heatmap by the specified parameters.¶

Parameters:

  • xys: The indecies of the boxes of which the overlap is to be found
  • window_size: the size if the window to crop the heatmap
  • img_size_tuple: the size of the heatmap to be returned
  • nob: the allowed `number of overlapping boxes` to be returned

    Returns:


  • heatmap: The image of overlapping boxes
  • Most overlapping indecies image (moi): An image most of overlapping boxes
In [144]:
def heat_map_over(xys,window_size,img_size_tuple,nob=3):
    img_height = img_size_tuple[0]
    img_width = img_size_tuple[1]
    
    heat_map = np.zeros((img_height,img_width)) # intialization
    most_overlap = np.zeros((img_height,img_width)) # intialization
    most_overlap3 = np.zeros((img_height,img_width)) # intialization

    imgs = np.zeros((len(xys),img_height,img_width)) #each rect in one image
    
    for k in range(len(xys)):
        i = xys[k][0] # x coord
        j = xys[k][1] # y coord
        imgs[k] = cv2.rectangle(imgs[k], (i, j), (i+window_size[k], j+window_size[k]), (1,0,0), -1)
   
    heat_map = np.sum(imgs,axis=0)
    heat_map2 = heat_map.copy()

    
    heat_map3 = heat_map.copy()

    for i in range(nob): # nob is num_overlapping_boxes
        max_intensity = np.max(heat_map3)
        moi = np.where(heat_map3==max_intensity) # most_overlap_indecies
        most_overlap3[moi]=1
        heat_map3[moi]=0
    
    return heat_map,most_overlap3 #heat_map,most_overlap

Now, to solve the issue of having too much yellow areas we have two options:¶

  • Connected heatmamps: calculating the heatmap not only from the current frame but also the next couple of frames
  • Yellow Cropping: having a sliding window of certain size the crops the large yellow ares and leaves out the small yello areas

    We went with second option, so we made two functions


  • wrapper: wrappes the process of: recognition and heatmap overlap in one function
  • draw boxes used inside wrapper, its perpose is to draw the recognition boxes after choosing certain yellow areas as cars

The following function wrapper() wrappes multiple functions insides of it, it returns the heatmap after being proccessed using the technique of yellow cropping¶

Parameters:

  • div: For recizing the image. The value will be mulitiplied by tthe original image dimenations
  • sliding_ratio_param: The sliding window overlapping percentage
  • nob_param: The maximum number of overlapping boxes to be output
  • box: if set to True, the function will return the boxes image, other wize it will return the moi and the heamap

    Returns:


  • boxed_image: The original image with the proccessed recognition boxes overlaid on to of it
    • OR:
  • moi: explained above
  • heatmap: explained above

def wrapper(div = 1, sliding_ratio_param = 1/4, nob_param = 7,test_img='vid/frame9721.jpg',box=False):
    test_img = cv2.imread(test_img)
    test_img = cv2.resize(test_img,(int(test_img.shape[1]/div),int(test_img.shape[0]/div)))
    test_img = cv2.cvtColor(test_img,cv2.COLOR_BGR2GRAY)
    test_img = cv2.GaussianBlur(test_img,(1,1),0)
    orginal = test_img.copy()
    out_img,ios = reco(test_img,div_size=1,rand_selection=False,slide_ratio=sliding_ratio_param)
#     plt.imshow(out_img)
    sizes = [64]*len(ios)
    heat_map,moi = heat_map_over(ios,sizes,out_img.shape,nob=nob_param)
#     plt.imshow(moi)
    if(not box):
        return moi,heat_map
    else:
        boxes_img = draw_boxes(moi,window_size=64,org_img1=orginal)
        return boxes_img,boxes_img

def draw_boxes(moi,window_size,org_img1,slide_ratio=1/4):
    org_img = org_img1.copy()
    copy1 = moi.copy()
    window_sizes = [window_size,int(window_size/1.2),int(window_size/1.5),int(window_size/2)]
    
    #   Sliding widow loop (not very efficent but works)
    
    for window_size in window_sizes:
        window = np.ones((window_size,window_size))
        max_error_sum = int(np.sum(window)*0.10)
        i=0
        while (i + window_size) < (copy1.shape[0]) : # y , vertical
            j=0
            while (j + window_size) < (copy1.shape[1]): # x , horizontal

                crop = copy1[i:window_size+i,j:window_size+j] # copy[vertical, horizontal]
                subtracted_img = window - crop # 
                match_sum = np.sum(subtracted_img) #
#                 error = int(0.25) #25% allowed error in moi
                if(match_sum<=max_error_sum):
                    copy1[i:window_size+i,j:window_size+j] = 0 # so we dont draw again
                    org_img = cv2.rectangle(org_img, (j,i), (j+window_size,i+window_size ), (255,0,0),2)

                j+= int(window_size*slide_ratio)
            i+= int(window_size*slide_ratio)
#         print(type(org_img))
#         org_img = org_img.astype('int')
    return org_img

Car collision detection¶

We initially planned to track the cars and measure the change of thier areas with respoect to frames, however that aproach is good but we also figured out that what if the car was on a different lane, and their area change increased dramatically , in out normal approach this behavoir will detect a collision where there is no collision since the car is in a different lane. So , we found out the we only concentrate on cars that are in our lane. So the following several sections well explain the procedure are detecting and tracking the lane

1- Detecting and tracking the lane¶

To detect the lane we do the following :

  • Cropped the image to a trapezoidal shape since the rest of the image will not be intersting to the line detection approach instead of adding more noise.
  • We apply canny edge detection on the image to detect the edges
  • We use hough transform on the cropped canny image to get a set of lines
  • the lines that we optain from the hough transorm are too much and we only need two line , so wee define a way ( or several ways ) to remove uneccessary lines

Reagion of interset methods are the ones that we use to be able to crop the image

In [2]:
def region_of_interest(img, vertices,match_mask_color = 255):
    mask = np.zeros_like(img)
    #channel_count = img.shape[2]
    #match_mask_color = 255
    cv2.fillPoly(mask, vertices, match_mask_color)
    
    masked_image = cv2.bitwise_and(img, mask)
    return masked_image
In [3]:
def region_of_interest2(img, vertices,match_mask_color = 255):
    mask = np.ones_like(img)
    #channel_count = img.shape[2]
    #match_mask_color = 255
    cv2.fillPoly(mask, vertices, match_mask_color)
    masked_image = cv2.bitwise_or(img, mask)
    return masked_image

The drow_the_lines mehods simply take an image and a list of lines and return the same image with the lines drawn in the image. The differnt versions of this image is becuase the input lines list may have differnt formats.

In [4]:
def drow_the_lines(img, lines):
    img = np.copy(img)
    blank_image = np.zeros((img.shape[0], img.shape[1], 3), dtype=np.uint8)
    

    for line in lines:
        for x1, y1, x2, y2 in line:
            cv2.line(blank_image, (x1,y1), (x2,y2), (0, 255, 0), thickness=10)

    img = cv2.addWeighted(img, 0.8, blank_image, 1, 0.0)
    return img
In [5]:
def drow_the_lines2(img, lines):
    img = np.copy(img)
    blank_image = np.zeros((img.shape[0], img.shape[1], 3), dtype=np.uint8)
    

    for line in lines:
        upperPoint = line[0] 
        lowerPoint = line[1] 
        cv2.line(blank_image, (upperPoint.x,upperPoint.y), (lowerPoint.x,lowerPoint.y), (0, 255, 0), thickness=10)

    img = cv2.addWeighted(img, 0.8, blank_image, 1, 0.0)
    return img
In [6]:
def drow_the_lines3(img, houghLines):
    img = np.copy(img)
    blank_image = np.zeros((img.shape[0], img.shape[1], 3), dtype=np.uint8)
    

    for houghLine in houghLines:
        #print("HERE ",houghLine.line.ravel())
        #for l in houghLine.line:
        x1,y1,x2,y2 = houghLine.line.ravel()
        cv2.line(blank_image, (x1,y1), (x2,y2), (0, 255, 0), thickness=10)

    img = cv2.addWeighted(img, 0.8, blank_image, 1, 0.0)
    return img

Deleting the rest of the lines¶

To do so , we created a method called deleteRepeatedLines wich takes houghlines ( a houghline is a class we created in shape_utils) and only returns two lines this is done by getting the slope of all the lines and taking the maximum positive slope ( the right line in the lane ) and the minimum negative slope ( the left line in the lane)

In [12]:
def deleteRepeatedLines(houghLines):
    minPos = 10000
    maxNeg  = -10000
    result = []
    global defaultLeftLine
    global defaultRightLine
    #defaultLeftLine = HoughLine(p1 = Point(300,720), p2 = Point(620,510))
    #defaultRightLine = HoughLine( p1 = Point(1280,720),p2 = Point(826,510))
        
    for line in houghLines:
        if line.getSlope() >0 and line.getSlope() < minPos :
            #minPos = lines.getSlope()
            #resultP.append(line)
            minPos = line.getSlope()

        if line.getSlope() <0 and line.getSlope() > maxNeg :
            #minPos = lines.getSlope()
            #resultP.append(line)
            maxNeg = line.getSlope()
            
    for line in houghLines :
        if line.getSlope() == minPos or line.getSlope() == maxNeg : 
            result.append(line)
    
    tmp = result.copy()
    if len(tmp) >=2 :
        for line in result :
            if line.getSlope() <0:
                tmp[0] = line
            else:
                tmp[1] = line
            
        result = tmp
    elif len(tmp) ==1 :
        if result[0].getSlope() < 0 :
            tmp[0] = result[0]
            #tmp.append(HoughLine( p1 = Point(1280,720),p2 = Point(826,510)))
            tmp.append(defaultRightLine)
        else :
            tmp[0] = result[0]
            #tmp.append(HoughLine(p1 = Point(300,720), p2 = Point(620,510)))
            tmp.append(defaultLeftLine)
        
        result = tmp
    elif len(tmp) ==0:
        #tmp.append(HoughLine(p1 = Point(300,720), p2 = Point(620,510)))
        #tmp.append(HoughLine( p1 = Point(1280,720),p2 = Point(826,510)))
        tmp.append(defaultLeftLine)
        tmp.append(defaultRightLine)
        
        
        result = tmp
    
    #defaultLeftLine = result[0]
    #defaultRightLine = result[1]
        
    return result

Now that we have two lines , we can extend them to be the lanes with the get getCompleterPoints method which takes an image a houghline and returns two points in that line, the upper point ( which is the point that lies on the top of the trapezoidal) and the lower point of the line (which is the point the lies in the base of the image)¶

In [14]:
def getCompleterPoints(img,line):
    img = np.copy(img)
    blank_image = np.zeros((img.shape[0], img.shape[1], 3), dtype=np.uint8)
    height = img.shape[0]
    y_upper = int(height/(3/2))+30
    y_lower = height
    
    upperPoint = Point(0,y_upper)
    lowerPoint = Point(0,y_lower)
    
    upperPoint.x = int(((y_upper - line.p1.y)+(line.getSlope()*line.p1.x))/line.getSlope())
    lowerPoint.x = int(((y_lower - line.p1.y)+(line.getSlope()*line.p1.x))/line.getSlope())
    result = [upperPoint,lowerPoint]
    
    return result

As we see above the code algorthm is too complicated. While we were developing this algorthm we discovered that there are many cases and its hard to find them manually , even if we managed to find them manually, each box will have a different shape that is inside the line wich then, calculating its area will not be straitforward, hence we found another way:¶

-Convolving the boxes with the image to determine the intersection size¶

To do so we make the detected lane black and then convolve the box with the image to see if the % of the box that is in the lane. In other words we will count the black pixels [ with value of 0] that are inside the box¶
So we created the method detectLane(img) that does all the explained code above and converts the lane into black¶

This method simply does all explained above to get the lines , then converts the lane to black using the follwoing code snippet

defaultLeftLine = HoughLine(p1 = Point(300,720), p2 = Point(620,510))

def detectLane(image, err = None):
    #image = cv2.cvtColor(image, cv2.COLOR_BGR2RGB)
    height = image.shape[0]
    width = image.shape[1]
    y_upper = int(height/(3/2))+30
    region_of_interest_vertices = [
        (0, height),
        ((width/3)+100, int(height/(3/2)) +30 ),
        (width/3+400, int(height/(3/2))+30 ),
        (width, height)
    ]
    
    gray_image = cv2.cvtColor(image, cv2.COLOR_RGB2GRAY)

    canny_image = cv2.Canny(gray_image, 50, 150)
    cropped_image = region_of_interest(canny_image,
                    np.array([region_of_interest_vertices], np.int32),)
    
    
    
    lines = cv2.HoughLinesP(cropped_image,
                        rho=6,
                        theta=np.pi/180,
                        threshold=90,
                        lines=np.array([]),
                        minLineLength=1,
                        maxLineGap=150)



    image_with_lines = drow_the_lines(image, lines)
    
    
    houghLines = []
    for line in lines:
        line = line.ravel()
        houghLines.append(HoughLine(line))
    
    


    finalLines = []
    for line in houghLines :
        if  line.getSlope() >0.4 or  line.getSlope() < -0.5:
            finalLines.append(line)


    image_with_lines = drow_the_lines3(image, finalLines)
    
    # Deleting repeted lines with trheshhold
    finalLines = deleteRepeatedLines(finalLines)
    image_with_lines = drow_the_lines3(image, finalLines)
    

    
    
    try :
        finalLines[0] =getCompleterPoints(image,finalLines[0])
    except IndexError :
        
        finalLines[0].append([Point(200,720),Point(526,510)])
        #print("finalLines[0] IndexError " )
        
        
    try :
        finalLines[1] =getCompleterPoints(image,finalLines[1])
    except IndexError :
        finalLines.append([(Point(1280,720),Point(826,510))])
        #print("finalLines[1]] IndexError " )
    
       
    
    leftRightLines = [HoughLine(p1 = finalLines[0][0],p2=finalLines[0][1]),HoughLine(p1 = finalLines[1][0],p2=finalLines[1][1])]
    
    
    
    for line in leftRightLines :
        if line.getSlope() < 0 :
            
            leftLine = line
        else : 
            rightLine = line
            
    leftLine = HoughLine(p1 = finalLines[0][0],p2=finalLines[0][1])
    rightLine = HoughLine(p1 = finalLines[1][0],p2=finalLines[1][1]) 
    
    road_verices = [
    leftLine.p1.getPoints(),
    leftLine.p2.getPoints(),
    rightLine.p2.getPoints(),
    rightLine.p1.getPoints()
]
    
    if len(finalLines) >2 :
        return err
    if(len(finalLines) ==0):
        finalLines.append([Point(200,720),Point(526,510)])
    if(len(finalLines) ==1):
        finalLines.append([Point(200,720),Point(526,510)])

    image_with_lines = drow_the_lines2(image, finalLines)
    
    cv2.fillPoly(image_with_lines, np.array([road_verices], np.int32), (0,0,0))
    
    return image_with_lines

The function below calculates the score of a box given its size , location and distance. The following is a snapshot from the method¶

slicedImage = img[box.y:box.y+box.h,box.x:box.x+box.w]

def getBoxScore(img,box,withDistance=False,boxPercentage = False):
    num_of_black = 0
    score = 0
    areaPercentage = 0
    dist = 0
    slicedImage = img[box.y:box.y+box.h,box.x:box.x+box.w]
    slicedImageArea = slicedImage.shape[0] * slicedImage.shape[1]
    ##print("Sliced image shape is ",slicedImage.shape)
    ##print("Box area is ",slicedImageArea)
    boxFilter = np.ones((box.w,box.h))
    
    if boxPercentage == False :
        unique , counts = np.unique(img,return_counts=True)
        num_of_black = counts[0]
        score = np.convolve(slicedImage.flatten(),boxFilter.flatten())
        unique , counts = np.unique(slicedImage,return_counts=True)
        areaPercentage = 100*(counts[0]/num_of_black)
    else :
        unique , counts = np.unique(slicedImage[:,:,0],return_counts=True)
        try :
            num_of_black = counts[0]
        except IndexError:
            box = Rectangle(0,0,0,0)
            areaPercentage = 0
            dist = 99999
            if withDistance == True : 
                return (areaPercentage,dist)
            return areaPercentage
        
        ##print(unique)
        
        areaPercentage = num_of_black/slicedImageArea
        ##print("Number of black is ",num_of_black,"\nBox area is ",slicedImageArea)
        

    
    plt.imshow(slicedImage)


    if withDistance == True : 
        dist = distanceFromBaseLine(img,box)
        #print("Distance :", dist)
        #print("Area ", areaPercentage)
        #return (areaPercentage / 0.01*dist)
        return (areaPercentage,dist)
    else :
        return areaPercentage
    

def distanceFromBaseLine(img,box):
    p0 = (box.l3[0],img.shape[0])
    p1 = (box.l3[0],box.l3[1])
    return math.sqrt((p0[0] - p1[0])**2 + (p0[1] - p1[1])**2)
